<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-09-07T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-09-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="425" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d425">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">841.857/32½</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Wilson</persName> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-09-07">
                                    <hi rend="italic">7 September, 1915</hi>.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: The sinking of the <hi rend="italic">Hesperian</hi><note n="49a" xml:id="d425fn1">For
                                correspondence previously printed regarding the <hi rend="italic">Hesperian</hi>, see <ref target="frus1915Supp#pg_533">
                                    <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, pp. 533</ref>–<ref target="frus1915Supp#pg_556">556</ref>
                                <hi rend="italic">passim</hi>, and <ref target="frus1915Supp#pg_607">p. 607</ref>.</note> has for the time arrested everything, and
                            therefore an answer to the enclosed<note n="50" xml:id="d425fn2">Nose of
                                Sept. 3, 1915, from the German Ambassador, <ref target="frus1915Supp#pg_533">
                                    <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, 533</ref>.</note> is perhaps too
                            much belated to be of any use to you. But this is clear, that we should
                            let the German Government know that it was not wise to wait too long to
                            state their attitude and the course they intend to pursue with regard to
                            the sinking of the <hi rend="italic">Arabic</hi>.</p>
                        <p>However, we shall not be certain of anything until we hear all the facts
                            about the <hi rend="italic">Hesperian</hi>.</p>
                        <p>Faithfully Yours,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>W. W.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>